{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"764e6753-853a-4b9b-a6d9-91708703f6da","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file. To focus on just the failing test:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nAs for the bug itself: `RemoveStock` never validates quantity — it just subtracts. It should throw when `quantity > available`. Here's the fix on line 37:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException($\"Cannot remove {quantity} of {sku}, only {current} available.\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply the fix and verify it passes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e010b032-3e16-4d7f-a22c-6cfb68f5e0d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. Since they're using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as indicated by `global.json`), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check if `dotnet watch test` works for this setup. With the Microsoft Testing Platform runner and .NET 10, the recommended approach is `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests on file changes.\n\nLet me set this up for them. But first, let me see if the test even builds/runs.\n\nActually, the user is asking how to set up hot reload. Let me just explain the approach. The simplest way is `dotnet watch test`, which will watch for file changes and re-run tests automatically.\n\n\nI could also filter to run just a specific test using the filter flag, which would be helpful if they want to focus on debugging a particular test case while iterating.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"4C31:1B1922:C48F27:F30C35:6A01328F"},"id":"b7f4b8ac-50ae-4dea-bfe1-35659299cec1","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:36:25.458Z","parentId":"986d24c6-52f6-43b4-93